2 \cos A \cdot \cos B = \cos (A +B) + \cos (A -B)
\displaystyle I = \int \cos{2x}\cos{nx}\;{dx}
\displaystyle J = \int\sin{2x}\sin{nx}\;{dx}
\displaystyle I+J = \int \cos{2x}\cos{nx}+\sin{2x}\sin{nx}\;{dx} = \int \cos(2x-nx)\;{dx}
\displaystyle I-J = \int \cos{2x}\cos{nx}-\sin{2x}\sin{nx}\;{dx} = \int \cos(2x+nx)\;{dx}
\displaystyle (I+J)+(I-J) = \frac{1}{2-n}\sin\left(2x-nx\right)+\frac{1}{2+n}\sin\left(2x+nx\right)+k
\displaystyle I = \frac{1}{4-2n}\sin\left(2x-nx\right)+\frac{1}{4+2n}\sin\left(2x+nx\right)+K.
